    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Mass transfer between the two stars in Algols has been inferred since 1955. However, it is unclear whether this mass transfer happens conservatively (all the material transferred from one star is accreted by the companion) or if systemic mass loss occurs. Indeed, there are more and more evidence suggesting non-conservative evolution (systemic angular momentum lack in interacting binaries, mismatch between conservative binary star models and observations, ...), but no direct detection have ever supported it so far. By analysing the WISE catalogue, we found three out-standing systems showing dusty environments that may originate from the mass transfer event. Unfortunately, the resolution given by WISE band 4 (12'') is too low to obtain any information on the mechanism at the origin of the outflow. We, therefore plan ALMA observations to better constrain the geometry and bring new light on the long-standing problematic of systemic mass loss in Algols.</prp:abstract>
